1
00:00:36,017 --> 00:00:39,116
Sometimes Dr. Lecter and I
would talk...

2
00:00:39,186 --> 00:00:41,095
when things got quiet enough...

3
00:00:41,169 --> 00:00:43,176
about the science courses
I was takin'.

4
00:00:43,249 --> 00:00:46,991
Some kind of mail-order courses
in psychology, Nurse Barney?

5
00:00:47,058 --> 00:00:48,432
No, sir.

6
00:00:48,497 --> 00:00:51,279
I don't consider psychology
a science...

7
00:00:51,346 --> 00:00:53,801
and neither did Dr. Lecter.

8
00:00:56,402 --> 00:00:57,896
Now, Barney...

9
00:00:57,970 --> 00:01:00,425
while you were working
at the asylum...

10
00:01:00,498 --> 00:01:06,313
you observed Clarice Starling
and Hannibal Lecter interacting.

11
00:01:06,385 --> 00:01:08,011
Interacting?

12
00:01:08,082 --> 00:01:10,733
Talking to one another.

13
00:01:10,802 --> 00:01:13,519
Yes.
Yes, it seemed to me that they...

14
00:01:13,586 --> 00:01:16,968
I can see you're eager to justify
your consulting fee...

15
00:01:17,041 --> 00:01:20,107
but why don't we start
with what you saw...

16
00:01:20,177 --> 00:01:22,152
not what you thought about
what you saw?

17
00:01:22,226 --> 00:01:26,503
Cordell, don't be like that.
Barney can give us his opinion.

18
00:01:26,578 --> 00:01:30,636
Barney, give us your opinion
of what you saw.

19
00:01:30,705 --> 00:01:33,007
What was it between them?

20
00:01:34,289 --> 00:01:38,315
Most of the time, Dr. Lecter
didn't respond at all to visitors.

21
00:01:38,385 --> 00:01:41,102
He'd just, for instance,
open his eyes long enough...

22
00:01:41,170 --> 00:01:44,203
to insult some academic
who was there to look over him.

23
00:01:45,682 --> 00:01:48,235
With Starling,
he answered her questions.

24
00:01:48,306 --> 00:01:51,950
She interested him.
She intrigued him.

25
00:01:52,017 --> 00:01:55,366
He thought she was charming
and amusing.

26
00:01:56,242 --> 00:01:59,111
So Clarice Starling
and Hannibal Lecter...

27
00:01:59,185 --> 00:02:02,000
became friendly.

28
00:02:02,065 --> 00:02:05,840
Inside a kind of formal structure,
yes.

29
00:02:05,905 --> 00:02:09,004
And he was fond of her.

30
00:02:11,250 --> 00:02:13,389
Yes.

31
00:02:13,458 --> 00:02:14,701
Thank you, Barney.

32
00:02:14,770 --> 00:02:16,712
Thank you very much
for your candor.

33
00:02:16,785 --> 00:02:19,949
And keep all those wonderful items...

34
00:02:20,017 --> 00:02:22,636
from your personal Lecter
treasure trove coming.

35
00:02:22,706 --> 00:02:24,429
I've enjoyed them immensely.

36
00:02:24,497 --> 00:02:26,155
Mr. Verger.

37
00:02:26,225 --> 00:02:28,647
Oh, I almost forgot.

38
00:02:28,722 --> 00:02:31,307
I might be able to get a cookie down.
What do you say, Cordell?

39
00:02:31,377 --> 00:02:33,744
I think it would kill you.

40
00:02:42,001 --> 00:02:44,816
How much?
Two hundred and fifty.

41
00:02:44,881 --> 00:02:46,605
Thousand.

42
00:02:48,305 --> 00:02:52,331
Cut a check for $250,000.

43
00:04:41,745 --> 00:04:44,047
How can she sleep
at a time like this?

44
00:04:45,457 --> 00:04:48,206
She's on a jump-out squad all night.
She's saving her strength.

45
00:05:16,785 --> 00:05:20,167
We got some guy named Bolton
from the DC Police.

46
00:05:21,457 --> 00:05:24,305
All right, everyone.
Pay attention. Here's the layout.

47
00:05:24,369 --> 00:05:26,857
Excuse me.
I'm Officer Bolton, DC Police.

48
00:05:26,930 --> 00:05:29,296
I can see that from your badge.
How do you do?

49
00:05:29,362 --> 00:05:30,823
I'm in charge here.

50
00:05:30,897 --> 00:05:33,036
Officer Bolton,
I'm Special Agent Starling.

51
00:05:33,105 --> 00:05:35,177
Just so we don't get off
on the wrong foot...

52
00:05:35,249 --> 00:05:37,354
let me explain
why we're all here.

53
00:05:37,425 --> 00:05:41,386
I'm here because I know Evelda Drumgo.
I arrested her twice on RICO warrants.

54
00:05:41,457 --> 00:05:43,977
DEA and ATF, in addition
to backing me up...

55
00:05:44,049 --> 00:05:45,991
are here for the drugs
and the weapons.

56
00:05:46,065 --> 00:05:48,880
You're here because our mayor
wants to appear tough on drugs...

57
00:05:48,945 --> 00:05:51,117
especially after his own
cocaine conviction...

58
00:05:51,186 --> 00:05:53,804
and hopes he can accomplish that
by having you join us here today.

59
00:05:54,705 --> 00:05:56,810
You got a smart mouth, lady.

60
00:05:56,881 --> 00:06:00,198
If you wouldn't mind, I'd appreciate it
if you'd let me continue.

61
00:06:01,489 --> 00:06:03,432
All right, take a look.

62
00:06:03,505 --> 00:06:06,353
Fish market.
Back's on the water.

63
00:06:06,417 --> 00:06:08,621
Across the street, ground floor,
is the meth lab.

64
00:06:08,689 --> 00:06:11,023
Evelda Drumgo's HIV positive.

65
00:06:11,089 --> 00:06:14,351
She will spit and bite if cornered,
so you should watch it.

66
00:06:14,417 --> 00:06:17,134
If you happen to be the one
who puts her in a patrol car...

67
00:06:17,201 --> 00:06:20,071
in front of the news cameras, Bolton,
you don't wanna push her head down.

68
00:06:20,145 --> 00:06:22,381
She'll likely have a needle
in her hair.

69
00:06:22,449 --> 00:06:25,133
We want to take her inside the building,
not out in the street.

70
00:06:25,201 --> 00:06:27,143
We can get closest with the van.

71
00:06:27,217 --> 00:06:30,184
If it looks good, on my signal
we hit the front, DEA hits the back...

72
00:06:30,257 --> 00:06:32,166
DCPD backin'them up.

73
00:06:32,241 --> 00:06:34,380
She'll have her watchers out
at least three blocks around.

74
00:06:35,281 --> 00:06:38,598
They've tipped her before in time, so
let's not make spectacles of ourselves.

75
00:06:50,161 --> 00:06:52,616
Pretty busy today.
I agree.

76
00:06:59,057 --> 00:07:00,845
Can I please get
a cup of coffee?

77
00:07:16,945 --> 00:07:19,116
Did you see that?
That's a roger.

78
00:07:27,442 --> 00:07:28,848
What's up, man?

79
00:07:38,449 --> 00:07:39,791
Goddamn it. It's her.

80
00:07:39,857 --> 00:07:42,029
With three guys.
They're all packin'.

81
00:07:42,097 --> 00:07:44,911
She's carryin' something.
She's got a baby.

82
00:07:44,977 --> 00:07:48,272
Hey, Brigham, it's too crowded.

83
00:07:48,337 --> 00:07:50,410
There are too many people.
I say we call it off.

84
00:07:50,481 --> 00:07:51,659
What do you say?

85
00:07:51,729 --> 00:07:53,704
I agree.

86
00:07:53,777 --> 00:07:56,013
All units, stand down.

87
00:07:56,081 --> 00:07:58,220
Whiskey team copies.
Burke copy.

88
00:07:58,289 --> 00:08:00,111
This is Bolton.
Stay on target.

89
00:08:00,177 --> 00:08:02,796
I said all units stand down, Bolton,
right now.

90
00:08:02,865 --> 00:08:04,905
It's too late. We're movin'in.
Bolton, he said it's off.

91
00:08:04,977 --> 00:08:06,668
Stand down now.

92
00:08:06,737 --> 00:08:08,647
She's carrying a baby.
I repeat, she's carrying a baby.

93
00:08:08,721 --> 00:08:11,110
All units stand down.

94
00:08:11,185 --> 00:08:13,127
Keep that gun down, Bolton.
Damn, dude got a piece.

95
00:08:13,201 --> 00:08:14,892
Light his ass up.
It's a go!

96
00:08:14,961 --> 00:08:16,390
FBI! Down on the ground!

97
00:08:56,977 --> 00:08:58,635
Hold it!

98
00:08:58,705 --> 00:09:00,614
Hold your fire!

99
00:09:02,545 --> 00:09:03,821
Don't!

100
00:09:06,705 --> 00:09:09,094
Evelda, get out of the car!

101
00:09:10,801 --> 00:09:12,459
Starling, is that you?

102
00:09:14,481 --> 00:09:16,521
Step away from the car!

103
00:09:18,065 --> 00:09:20,072
Show me your hands, Evelda.

104
00:09:21,745 --> 00:09:24,712
Please.
Show me your hands.

105
00:09:24,785 --> 00:09:26,312
How've you been?

106
00:09:26,385 --> 00:09:28,010
Don't do this.

107
00:09:28,081 --> 00:09:29,128
Do what?

108
00:10:00,081 --> 00:10:02,253
It's all right. It's okay.

109
00:10:02,321 --> 00:10:05,190
I know, I know. Baby, I know.

110
00:10:05,265 --> 00:10:07,632
It's okay.

111
00:10:07,697 --> 00:10:09,836
It's okay.

112
00:10:10,929 --> 00:10:12,839
It's okay.

113
00:10:30,865 --> 00:10:33,101
Friends, family and coworkers
gathered here this morning...

114
00:10:33,169 --> 00:10:37,130
at Arlington National Cemetery
to bury BATF AgentJohn Brigham...

115
00:10:37,201 --> 00:10:40,430
shot and killed in the line of duty
Friday. He was 40 years old.

116
00:10:40,497 --> 00:10:43,661
This ill-fated drug raid that claimed
his life and five others...

117
00:10:43,729 --> 00:10:46,217
is the latest in a seemingly
endless series of incidents...

118
00:10:46,289 --> 00:10:48,012
beginning with Waco, Texas...

119
00:10:48,081 --> 00:10:51,310
in which theJustice Department
and the FBI have been questioned...

120
00:10:51,377 --> 00:10:54,159
about their use of firepower
rather than judgment.

121
00:10:54,225 --> 00:10:56,778
This time it was FBI
Special Agent Clarice Starling...

122
00:10:56,849 --> 00:10:58,540
heading up
the calamitous strike force.

123
00:10:58,609 --> 00:11:02,056
Agent Starling attained some measure
of celebrity ten years ago...

124
00:11:02,129 --> 00:11:05,358
when she was given information
by Dr. Hannibal "The Cannibal"Lecter...

125
00:11:05,425 --> 00:11:07,497
which led to the rescue
of Catherine Martin...

126
00:11:07,569 --> 00:11:09,871
daughter of the former US senator
from Tennessee.

127
00:11:09,937 --> 00:11:13,581
When she returns to work this week,
she won't be so celebrated.

128
00:11:13,649 --> 00:11:16,497
Attorney Telford Higgins, representing
one of the families of those slain...

129
00:11:16,561 --> 00:11:19,212
says he will file
a wrongful-death suit.

130
00:11:20,561 --> 00:11:22,285
Cordell!

131
00:11:33,649 --> 00:11:36,399
Yes, sir.
Get me theJustice Department.

132
00:11:43,889 --> 00:11:45,612
Agent Starling?

133
00:11:45,681 --> 00:11:49,293
This is John Eldridge from DEA.
Assistant Director Noonan, you know.

134
00:11:49,361 --> 00:11:52,395
Larkin Wayne from our Office
of Professional Responsibility.

135
00:11:52,465 --> 00:11:54,374
Bob Sneed, ATF.

136
00:11:54,449 --> 00:11:57,515
Benny Holcombe, assistant to the mayor.
And Paul Krendler.

137
00:11:57,585 --> 00:12:00,006
You know Paul.
Paul's come over from Justice...

138
00:12:00,081 --> 00:12:02,503
unofficially,
as a favor to us.

139
00:12:02,577 --> 00:12:04,998
In other words, he's here,
and he's not here.

140
00:12:07,857 --> 00:12:10,792
So I take it you've seen the coverage
in the papers and on television?

141
00:12:10,865 --> 00:12:13,352
I have nothing to do with the news,
Mr. Krendler.

142
00:12:13,424 --> 00:12:16,108
The woman had a baby in her arms.

143
00:12:16,177 --> 00:12:19,046
There are pictures. You could
see the problem, I would think.

144
00:12:19,121 --> 00:12:22,318
Not in her arms.
In a carrier across her chest.

145
00:12:22,385 --> 00:12:24,457
In her arms she had a MAC-10.

146
00:12:24,529 --> 00:12:27,496
Look, we're here to help you,
Starling.

147
00:12:27,569 --> 00:12:30,439
It's gonna be a hell of a lot harder
to do with a combative attitude.

148
00:12:35,377 --> 00:12:37,798
Can I speak freely, Mr. Pearsall?

149
00:12:39,409 --> 00:12:42,376
Your agency called this office to get me
assigned to help you on this raid.

150
00:12:42,449 --> 00:12:44,336
I tried to do that.

151
00:12:44,400 --> 00:12:47,302
I clearly expressed my judgment
and was ignored.

152
00:12:47,376 --> 00:12:50,311
And now a good agent and a friend
is dead.

153
00:12:53,329 --> 00:12:55,817
You shot and killed five people
out there, Agent Starling.

154
00:12:55,889 --> 00:12:57,994
Is that how you define
good judgment?

155
00:12:58,896 --> 00:13:00,936
This raid was an ugly mess.

156
00:13:01,009 --> 00:13:04,009
I ended up in a position
where I had a choice of dying...

157
00:13:04,081 --> 00:13:06,023
or shooting a woman
carrying a child.

158
00:13:06,097 --> 00:13:08,268
I chose.

159
00:13:08,337 --> 00:13:09,930
I shot her.

160
00:13:10,801 --> 00:13:13,190
I killed a mother
holding her child.

161
00:13:15,216 --> 00:13:17,605
And I regret it.
I resent myself for it.

162
00:13:17,681 --> 00:13:20,103
Gentlemen, I'm going
to call a halt to this meeting...

163
00:13:20,176 --> 00:13:22,478
and get back to you individually
by phone.

164
00:13:26,705 --> 00:13:28,592
That was a waste of time.

165
00:13:30,289 --> 00:13:32,558
You have a secret admirer, Starling.

166
00:13:32,625 --> 00:13:36,040
He isn't much to look at,
but he does have friends in high places.

167
00:13:37,104 --> 00:13:39,821
Remember Mason Verger?

168
00:13:39,889 --> 00:13:42,376
Lecter's fourth victim.

169
00:13:42,449 --> 00:13:43,911
The rich one.

170
00:13:43,985 --> 00:13:46,286
The only one that survived.

171
00:13:47,408 --> 00:13:49,929
He says he has some new information
on Lecter he'll only share with you.

172
00:13:50,001 --> 00:13:53,514
What do you mean, only share it with me?
You want it, seize it.

173
00:13:53,585 --> 00:13:56,618
I'd rather not.
I wasn't speaking to you.

174
00:13:56,689 --> 00:13:59,078
When I speak to you, you'll know it
because I'll look at you.

175
00:14:00,785 --> 00:14:02,214
Why would we rather not?

176
00:14:02,289 --> 00:14:05,769
The last time he called was when we took
Lecter off the Ten Most Wanted List.

177
00:14:06,864 --> 00:14:09,231
He was upset about that.
We said, "Hey, that's life."

178
00:14:09,297 --> 00:14:12,493
He said, "This is a Senate
Oversight Committee...

179
00:14:12,561 --> 00:14:14,088
to make your life miserable. "

180
00:14:14,161 --> 00:14:17,063
His family's political contributions
may not be enough...

181
00:14:17,137 --> 00:14:18,795
to buy a senator...

182
00:14:18,865 --> 00:14:20,774
but they are enough
to rent them from time to time.

183
00:14:21,585 --> 00:14:25,032
There's no reason to go through that
if he really does have something new.

184
00:14:27,024 --> 00:14:30,854
It's a good deal for you, Starling.
You can't pretend it isn't.

185
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:34,088
Get to go back
on a celebrated case.

186
00:14:34,161 --> 00:14:37,422
I'll take care of the media
for your Drumgo killing.

187
00:14:37,488 --> 00:14:38,830
Everyone's gonna be happy.

188
00:14:38,896 --> 00:14:41,864
I'm not happy.

189
00:14:41,937 --> 00:14:44,620
Well, maybe you're incapable
of being happy.

190
00:14:45,616 --> 00:14:47,656
Mr. Krendler...

191
00:14:47,984 --> 00:14:51,115
out on the street, you know you might
take a bullet in the line of duty.

192
00:14:51,185 --> 00:14:53,519
You accept it or you get out.

193
00:14:53,585 --> 00:14:55,341
You live with it.

194
00:14:55,409 --> 00:14:58,027
What you don't expect or accept...

195
00:14:58,096 --> 00:15:00,649
is taking one in the back
in your boss's office...

196
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:02,825
for doing your job
exactly as they've taught you.

197
00:15:02,896 --> 00:15:04,489
That makes you unhappy.

198
00:15:04,560 --> 00:15:07,822
Of course you're right, Starling...

199
00:15:07,889 --> 00:15:09,831
but it doesn't change anything.

200
00:15:09,905 --> 00:15:12,971
It changes everything.
It changes me.

201
00:16:01,585 --> 00:16:04,618
Hi, I'm Cordell Doemling,
Mr. Verger's private physician.

202
00:16:04,688 --> 00:16:06,215
How do you do?

203
00:16:06,289 --> 00:16:09,638
If you'd be so kind
as to park down at the end.

204
00:16:14,704 --> 00:16:17,421
One's eyes adjust to the darkness.

205
00:16:32,209 --> 00:16:35,340
Mr. Verger,
Agent Starling is here.

206
00:16:35,408 --> 00:16:38,092
Good morning, Mr. Verger.

207
00:16:38,161 --> 00:16:40,430
Was that a Mustang
I heard out there?

208
00:16:40,497 --> 00:16:41,577
Yes, it was.

209
00:16:41,649 --> 00:16:43,437
Five-liter?

210
00:16:43,504 --> 00:16:45,097
Yes.

211
00:16:45,168 --> 00:16:47,503
Fast.

212
00:16:47,569 --> 00:16:50,024
Cordell, I think
you can leave us now.

213
00:16:50,097 --> 00:16:54,320
I thought I might stay.
Perhaps I could be useful.

214
00:16:54,385 --> 00:16:58,411
You could be useful
seeing about my lunch.

215
00:17:02,896 --> 00:17:06,191
I'll attach this microphone to your
clothing or pillow, if that's okay.

216
00:17:06,257 --> 00:17:08,297
By all means.

217
00:17:13,200 --> 00:17:15,110
Here, this should make it easier.

218
00:17:22,577 --> 00:17:24,966
You know, I thank God...

219
00:17:25,040 --> 00:17:26,829
for what happened.

220
00:17:26,896 --> 00:17:28,969
It was my salvation.

221
00:17:30,257 --> 00:17:33,421
Have you accepted Jesus,
Agent Starling?

222
00:17:33,489 --> 00:17:35,944
Do you have faith?
I was raised Lutheran.

223
00:17:36,017 --> 00:17:38,504
That's not what I asked.

224
00:17:38,576 --> 00:17:41,838
This is Special Agent
Clarice Starling, 5143690...

225
00:17:41,904 --> 00:17:44,621
deposing Mason R. Verger on March 20,
sworn and attested.

226
00:17:44,688 --> 00:17:47,536
I want to tell you about summer camp.
It was a wonderful childhood experience.

227
00:17:47,601 --> 00:17:50,470
We can get to that later.
We can get to it now.

228
00:17:51,408 --> 00:17:53,350
You see, it all comes to bear.

229
00:17:53,424 --> 00:17:57,767
It was a Christian camp
my father founded...

230
00:17:57,841 --> 00:18:02,183
for poor, unfortunate, cast-off
little boys and girls...

231
00:18:02,256 --> 00:18:04,907
who would do anything
for a candy bar.

232
00:18:04,977 --> 00:18:07,432
Mr. Verger, I don't need to know
about the sex offenses.

233
00:18:07,505 --> 00:18:10,821
It's all right.
I have immunity from the US Attorney.

234
00:18:10,896 --> 00:18:12,968
And I have immunity...

235
00:18:13,040 --> 00:18:15,910
from the risen Jesus.

236
00:18:15,985 --> 00:18:18,406
And nobody beats the Riz.

237
00:18:19,088 --> 00:18:22,219
Had you ever seen Dr. Lecter before the
court assigned you to him for therapy?

238
00:18:22,288 --> 00:18:23,630
What do you mean?

239
00:18:23,696 --> 00:18:25,420
Socially?

240
00:18:26,961 --> 00:18:30,027
It is what I mean, yes,
if you don't mind talking about it.

241
00:18:30,096 --> 00:18:32,005
No, not at all.
I'm not ashamed.

242
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:35,211
I didn't say you should be.
No, we met conventionally...

243
00:18:35,281 --> 00:18:37,255
as doctor and patient.

244
00:18:37,328 --> 00:18:39,051
How did he end up at your house?

245
00:18:39,121 --> 00:18:41,935
I invited him, of course...

246
00:18:43,025 --> 00:18:45,610
to my pied-a-terre.

247
00:18:45,680 --> 00:18:49,706
I came to the door
in my nicest come-hither outfit.

248
00:18:49,776 --> 00:18:51,686
I was concerned...

249
00:18:51,761 --> 00:18:54,957
that he'd be afraid of me.

250
00:18:55,024 --> 00:18:58,286
But he didn't seem to be
afraid of me.

251
00:18:59,376 --> 00:19:01,416
That's almost funny now.

252
00:19:02,704 --> 00:19:04,712
I showed him my toys...

253
00:19:04,784 --> 00:19:07,599
my noose setup,
among other things.

254
00:19:07,664 --> 00:19:11,756
It's where you sort of hang yourself,
but not really.

255
00:19:11,825 --> 00:19:13,832
It feels good while you...

256
00:19:14,705 --> 00:19:16,647
well, you know.

257
00:19:16,721 --> 00:19:17,997
Anyway...

258
00:19:18,064 --> 00:19:22,407
he said, "Mason..."
Mason, would you like a popper?

259
00:19:23,345 --> 00:19:26,694
And I said, "Would I? Oh, wow!"

260
00:19:26,769 --> 00:19:29,387
Once that kicked in,
I was flying.

261
00:19:29,457 --> 00:19:33,199
He said,
"Mason, show me how you smile...

262
00:19:33,264 --> 00:19:36,712
to gain the confidence
of a child. "

263
00:19:36,785 --> 00:19:39,632
When I smiled...

264
00:19:39,696 --> 00:19:42,511
he said,
"Oh, I see how you do it."

265
00:19:42,576 --> 00:19:47,116
The good doctor approached me
with a piece of broken mirror.

266
00:19:47,185 --> 00:19:48,199
"Try this."

267
00:19:49,361 --> 00:19:51,084
Try peeling off your face...

268
00:19:51,889 --> 00:19:54,474
And feeding it to the dogs.

269
00:20:03,409 --> 00:20:06,059
No, I can still see it.

270
00:20:06,128 --> 00:20:07,241
Try again.

271
00:20:08,369 --> 00:20:10,824
No, I'm afraid not.

272
00:20:10,896 --> 00:20:13,481
That's entertainment

273
00:20:15,568 --> 00:20:18,917
Well, it seemed like
a good idea at the time.

274
00:20:20,208 --> 00:20:23,885
You indicated to me that you'd received
some kind of new information.

275
00:20:41,488 --> 00:20:43,757
Where did this come from?

276
00:20:43,825 --> 00:20:46,792
Buenos Aires.
I received it two weeks ago.

277
00:20:48,560 --> 00:20:51,048
Where's the package it came in?

278
00:20:51,120 --> 00:20:54,502
Good question. There was nothing
written on it of interest.

279
00:20:54,576 --> 00:20:56,365
Did we throw it out?

280
00:20:57,456 --> 00:20:59,366
Yes, I'm afraid we did.

281
00:20:59,441 --> 00:21:02,091
Oh, dear.
You think it'll help?

282
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:04,102
I hope so.

283
00:21:04,176 --> 00:21:06,086
I hope it'll help you catch him...

284
00:21:06,161 --> 00:21:10,830
to help cleanse the stigma
of your recent dishonor.

285
00:21:10,896 --> 00:21:12,489
Thank you. That's all I need.

286
00:21:12,560 --> 00:21:15,430
Did you find some rapport
with Dr. Lecter...

287
00:21:15,504 --> 00:21:17,926
in your talks at the asylum?

288
00:21:19,216 --> 00:21:21,933
I know I did
while I was peeling.

289
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:24,815
We exchanged information
in a civil way.

290
00:21:24,880 --> 00:21:27,302
But always through the glass.

291
00:21:27,376 --> 00:21:28,871
Yes.

292
00:21:38,705 --> 00:21:41,934
Isn't it funny?
What's that?

293
00:21:42,608 --> 00:21:44,517
You can look at my face...

294
00:21:45,808 --> 00:21:49,005
but you shied when I said
the name of God.

295
00:22:14,256 --> 00:22:17,420
Finding what you want?
Are you sure this is all of it?

296
00:22:17,488 --> 00:22:19,430
That's all there is now.

297
00:22:19,504 --> 00:22:22,799
There was more, but it's been picked
over little by little over the years.

298
00:22:24,240 --> 00:22:27,688
You know, this stuff's worth
a lot of money in certain circles.

299
00:22:29,296 --> 00:22:31,500
It's kind of like the cocaine
that disappears around here...

300
00:22:31,568 --> 00:22:32,877
little by little.

301
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:55,756
Hey, Barney.

302
00:23:55,824 --> 00:23:58,093
Remember me?

303
00:23:58,161 --> 00:24:00,397
Would you agree for the record,
Agent Starling...

304
00:24:00,464 --> 00:24:02,220
that I've not been read my rights?

305
00:24:06,256 --> 00:24:10,860
I have not Mirandized Barney.
He is unaware of his rights.

306
00:24:12,496 --> 00:24:14,798
So when you turned Dr. Lecter over
to the Tennessee police...

307
00:24:14,864 --> 00:24:18,792
They weren't civil to him.
They're all dead now.

308
00:24:18,864 --> 00:24:21,101
They only survived his company
three days.

309
00:24:21,168 --> 00:24:23,917
You survived him
six years at the asylum.

310
00:24:23,984 --> 00:24:27,017
How'd you do that?
It wasn't just being civil.

311
00:24:27,088 --> 00:24:29,739
Yes, it was.

312
00:24:29,808 --> 00:24:32,939
Did you ever think, after he escaped,
he might come after you?

313
00:24:33,008 --> 00:24:34,023
No.

314
00:24:34,096 --> 00:24:36,300
He once told me that,
whenever feasible...

315
00:24:36,368 --> 00:24:38,375
he preferred to eat the rude.

316
00:24:38,448 --> 00:24:42,409
"Free-range rude," he called 'em.
What about you?

317
00:24:42,480 --> 00:24:45,709
You ever think he might come after you?
You ever think about him at all?

318
00:24:45,776 --> 00:24:49,038
At least 30 seconds of every day.
I can't help it.

319
00:24:49,104 --> 00:24:51,853
He's always with me,
like a bad habit.

320
00:24:53,136 --> 00:24:56,910
Do you know what happened to his stuff...
his books, papers, drawings?

321
00:24:56,976 --> 00:24:59,594
Everything got thrown away
when the place closed.

322
00:24:59,664 --> 00:25:01,769
Cutbacks.

323
00:25:01,840 --> 00:25:04,938
I just found out that Dr. Lecter's
signed copy of TheJoy of Cooking...

324
00:25:05,008 --> 00:25:08,391
sold to a private collector
for $16,000.

325
00:25:09,488 --> 00:25:11,593
It was probably a fake.

326
00:25:11,664 --> 00:25:15,494
The seller's affidavit of ownership
was signed "Karen Phlox."

327
00:25:15,568 --> 00:25:18,700
Do you know Karen Phlox?
You should.

328
00:25:18,768 --> 00:25:22,543
She filled out your employment
application, but signed it "Barney."

329
00:25:23,440 --> 00:25:25,612
Same thing on your tax returns.

330
00:25:28,400 --> 00:25:32,175
You want the book?
Maybe I can get it back.

331
00:25:32,240 --> 00:25:36,496
I want the x-ray of Lecter's arm
you broke in the attack on that nurse...

332
00:25:36,560 --> 00:25:38,600
and everything else you've got.

333
00:25:42,416 --> 00:25:45,994
We used to talk about
a lot of things at night...

334
00:25:46,064 --> 00:25:48,814
after the screamin'
finally died down.

335
00:25:52,336 --> 00:25:56,613
We talked about you sometimes.
You wanna know what he said?

336
00:25:56,688 --> 00:25:58,860
Go get the x-ray.

337
00:26:04,688 --> 00:26:06,630
I'm not a bad guy.

338
00:26:06,704 --> 00:26:08,230
I didn't say you were.

339
00:26:08,304 --> 00:26:10,693
Dr. Chilton was a bad guy.

340
00:26:10,768 --> 00:26:14,794
After your first visit, he started
taping your conversations with Lecter.

341
00:26:17,136 --> 00:26:19,591
These are valuable.

342
00:26:24,816 --> 00:26:26,791
Go on now.

343
00:26:26,864 --> 00:26:29,165
You've grieved long enough.

344
00:26:33,200 --> 00:26:35,272
And what'd he say?

345
00:26:35,344 --> 00:26:37,254
What'd he say about me
late at night?

346
00:26:38,544 --> 00:26:41,293
He was talking about
inherited, hardwired behavior.

347
00:26:41,360 --> 00:26:44,230
He was using genetics
in the roller pigeons as an example.

348
00:26:44,304 --> 00:26:48,810
They fly up in the air, roll backwards
in a display, fallin' to the ground.

349
00:26:48,880 --> 00:26:52,175
There are shallow rollers,
and there are deep rollers.

350
00:26:52,240 --> 00:26:54,182
You can't breed two deep rollers...

351
00:26:54,256 --> 00:26:57,354
or their young, their offspring,
will roll all the way down...

352
00:26:57,424 --> 00:26:59,628
hit and die.

353
00:26:59,696 --> 00:27:02,631
Agent Starling is a deep roller,
Barney.

354
00:27:02,704 --> 00:27:06,152
Let us hope one of her parents
was not.

355
00:27:06,223 --> 00:27:09,769
Surely the odd confluence of events
hasn't escaped you, Clarice.

356
00:27:11,056 --> 00:27:13,838
Jack Crawford dangles you
in front of me...

357
00:27:13,903 --> 00:27:16,489
then I give you a bit of help.

358
00:27:16,560 --> 00:27:18,796
Do you think it's because
I like to look at you...

359
00:27:18,864 --> 00:27:22,638
and imagine how good
you would taste...

360
00:27:22,704 --> 00:27:24,940
Clarice?

361
00:27:25,008 --> 00:27:27,496
I don't know. Is it?

362
00:27:29,584 --> 00:27:32,005
I've been in this room
for eight years now, Clarice.

363
00:27:32,784 --> 00:27:35,686
I know they will never, ever
let me out while I'm alive.

364
00:27:36,976 --> 00:27:39,016
What I want is a view.

365
00:27:39,088 --> 00:27:42,830
I want a window where I
can see a tree or even water.

366
00:27:42,896 --> 00:27:45,711
I want to be in a federal institution
far away from Dr. Chilton.

367
00:27:58,704 --> 00:28:02,020
The Capponi correspondence
goes back to the 13th century.

368
00:28:02,096 --> 00:28:04,780
Dr. Fell might hold in his hand...

369
00:28:04,848 --> 00:28:06,822
his non-Italian hand...

370
00:28:06,896 --> 00:28:09,230
a note from Dante Alighieri himself.

371
00:28:09,296 --> 00:28:12,045
But would he recognize it?
I think not.

372
00:28:13,168 --> 00:28:16,430
Gentlemen, you have examined him
in medieval Italian...

373
00:28:16,496 --> 00:28:19,017
and I will not deny
that his language is admirable...

374
00:28:19,088 --> 00:28:21,226
for a straniero.

375
00:28:21,296 --> 00:28:24,427
But is he acquainted
with the personalities...

376
00:28:24,496 --> 00:28:26,154
of the pre-Renaissance Firenze?

377
00:28:27,056 --> 00:28:28,966
I think not.

378
00:28:29,039 --> 00:28:31,625
What if he came upon a note
in the Capponi library...

379
00:28:31,696 --> 00:28:34,184
say from Guido di Cavalcanti?

380
00:28:34,256 --> 00:28:37,900
Would he recognize that?
I think not.

381
00:28:37,968 --> 00:28:40,302
They're still arguing?

382
00:28:43,024 --> 00:28:45,577
Sogliato wants the job
for his nephew.

383
00:28:45,648 --> 00:28:50,023
But the scholars seem satisfied
with the temporary guy they appointed.

384
00:28:50,096 --> 00:28:52,584
If he's such an expert on Dante...

385
00:28:52,656 --> 00:28:55,339
let him lecture on Dante
to the Studiolo.

386
00:28:55,408 --> 00:28:58,158
Let him face them if he can.
I look forward to it.

387
00:29:00,208 --> 00:29:02,696
Very well. On the 14th.

388
00:29:19,055 --> 00:29:21,608
Dr. Fell?

389
00:29:21,680 --> 00:29:24,331
Chief Inspector Rinaldo Pazzi
of the questura.

390
00:29:24,496 --> 00:29:27,812
Commendatore,
how can I be of service?

391
00:29:27,888 --> 00:29:30,638
Sorry. I'm investigating
the disappearance...

392
00:29:30,704 --> 00:29:34,795
of your predecessor,
Signor di Bonaventura.

393
00:29:34,864 --> 00:29:37,581
I was wondering if...
"Predecessor" implies I have the job.

394
00:29:37,648 --> 00:29:41,226
Unfortunately, I don't.
Not yet, though I am hopeful.

395
00:29:41,295 --> 00:29:44,940
They are letting me look after
the library for a stipend.

396
00:29:46,640 --> 00:29:48,713
The officers who first checked...

397
00:29:48,784 --> 00:29:52,712
didn't find any sort of farewell
or suicide note.

398
00:29:52,784 --> 00:29:54,245
I was wondering if you...

399
00:29:54,320 --> 00:29:57,833
If I come across anything in the Capponi
library stuffed in a drawer or book...

400
00:29:57,904 --> 00:29:59,759
I'll call you at once.

401
00:30:01,776 --> 00:30:03,564
Thank you.

402
00:30:04,528 --> 00:30:06,317
You've been reassigned.

403
00:30:09,296 --> 00:30:10,408
Pardon?

404
00:30:10,480 --> 00:30:13,775
You were on the II Mostro case,
I'm sure I read.

405
00:30:13,840 --> 00:30:16,109
Yes, that's right.
Now you're on this.

406
00:30:16,176 --> 00:30:19,023
This is much less grand a case,
I would think.

407
00:30:19,087 --> 00:30:22,633
Well, if I thought of my work
in those terms...

408
00:30:22,704 --> 00:30:24,231
yes, I guess I'd agree.

409
00:30:24,976 --> 00:30:27,310
A missing person.
Sorry?

410
00:30:27,375 --> 00:30:31,172
Were you unfairly dismissed from
the grander case, or did you deserve it?

411
00:30:37,008 --> 00:30:39,626
Regarding this one, Dr. Fell...

412
00:30:39,695 --> 00:30:42,543
are the signore's personal effects
still at the Palazzo?

413
00:30:44,080 --> 00:30:47,495
Packed neatly in four cases
with an inventory.

414
00:30:47,568 --> 00:30:50,088
Alas, no note.

415
00:30:52,560 --> 00:30:56,815
I'll send someone over to pick them up.
Thank you for your help.

416
00:31:07,183 --> 00:31:08,874
Hey, thanks.

417
00:31:10,415 --> 00:31:12,422
How's it going? Any leads?

418
00:31:12,495 --> 00:31:15,495
Yeah, they're all leads.
They just don't lead to him.

419
00:31:20,015 --> 00:31:21,925
I don't know how you live
with this stuff.

420
00:31:21,999 --> 00:31:24,388
Oh, God.

421
00:31:24,463 --> 00:31:26,984
This is from the Guinness Book
of World Records congratulating me...

422
00:31:27,056 --> 00:31:30,536
on being the female FBI agent
who has shot and killed the most people.

423
00:31:53,136 --> 00:31:55,045
Would you excuse me, please?

424
00:31:56,976 --> 00:31:59,114
Sure.

425
00:32:23,439 --> 00:32:24,846
Dear Clarice...

426
00:32:26,288 --> 00:32:30,182
I've followed with enthusiasm the course
of your disgrace and public shaming.

427
00:32:30,255 --> 00:32:33,419
My own never bothered me
except for the inconvenience...

428
00:32:33,487 --> 00:32:35,276
of being incarcerated.

429
00:32:35,344 --> 00:32:37,580
But you may lack perspective.

430
00:32:38,864 --> 00:32:40,904
In our discussions
down in the dungeon...

431
00:32:40,975 --> 00:32:44,652
it was apparent to me that your father,
the dead night watchman...

432
00:32:44,720 --> 00:32:47,175
figures largely
in your value system.

433
00:32:48,655 --> 00:32:52,779
I think your success in putting an end
toJame Gumb's career as a couturier...

434
00:32:52,847 --> 00:32:57,288
pleased you most because you could
imagine your father being pleased.

435
00:32:57,360 --> 00:33:01,037
But now, alas,
you're in bad odor with the FBI.

436
00:33:01,104 --> 00:33:03,689
Do you imagine your daddy
being shamed by your disgrace?

437
00:33:03,759 --> 00:33:06,629
Do you see him
in his plain pine box...

438
00:33:06,704 --> 00:33:08,613
crushed by your failure...

439
00:33:08,688 --> 00:33:11,917
the sorry, petty end
of a promising career?

440
00:33:11,983 --> 00:33:15,366
What is worst
about this humiliation, Clarice?

441
00:33:15,439 --> 00:33:19,051
Is it how your failure will reflect
on your mommy and daddy?

442
00:33:20,464 --> 00:33:23,115
Is your worst fear that people
will now and forever believe...

443
00:33:23,184 --> 00:33:26,086
they were indeed just good old
trailer-camp...

444
00:33:26,160 --> 00:33:28,298
tornado-bait white trash...

445
00:33:28,367 --> 00:33:30,604
and that perhaps you are too?

446
00:33:33,648 --> 00:33:36,648
By the way, I couldn't help noticing
on the FBI's rather dull web site...

447
00:33:36,720 --> 00:33:41,422
that I've been hoisted from the Bureau's
archives of the common criminal...

448
00:33:41,488 --> 00:33:44,488
and elevated to the more prestigious
Ten Most Wanted List.

449
00:33:45,903 --> 00:33:49,929
Is this coincidence,
or are you back on the case?

450
00:33:49,999 --> 00:33:53,348
If so, goody goody, because
I need to come out of retirement...

451
00:33:53,423 --> 00:33:55,725
and return to public life.

452
00:33:58,896 --> 00:34:01,383
I imagine you sitting
in a dark basement room...

453
00:34:01,455 --> 00:34:04,390
bent over papers
and computer screens.

454
00:34:04,464 --> 00:34:06,406
Is that accurate?

455
00:34:06,480 --> 00:34:10,636
Please tell me truly,
Special Agent Starling.

456
00:34:10,703 --> 00:34:15,340
Regards, your old pal,
Hannibal Lecter, MD.

457
00:34:16,975 --> 00:34:21,067
PS: : Clearly this new assignment
is not your choice.

458
00:34:21,136 --> 00:34:23,045
Rather, I suppose,
it is part of the bargain.

459
00:34:23,120 --> 00:34:25,837
But you accepted it, Clarice.

460
00:34:25,903 --> 00:34:28,423
Yourjob is to craft my doom...

461
00:34:28,495 --> 00:34:31,179
so I'm not sure how well
I should wish you...

462
00:34:31,248 --> 00:34:33,615
but I'm sure
we'll have a lot of fun.

463
00:34:33,680 --> 00:34:35,338
Ta-ta.

464
00:34:35,407 --> 00:34:37,414
"H."

465
00:34:43,343 --> 00:34:44,553
On the letter...

466
00:34:44,624 --> 00:34:47,340
there's one partial fingerprint here.

467
00:34:47,408 --> 00:34:50,375
Not enough to hold up in court.
I know it's him.

468
00:34:50,448 --> 00:34:52,619
Where he was when he wrote it
is what I need.

469
00:34:52,687 --> 00:34:54,956
Well, the paper isn't gonna help.

470
00:34:55,023 --> 00:34:57,838
Yes, it's linen fibre,
yes, it's on the expensive side...

471
00:34:57,903 --> 00:35:02,093
but it's not so rare that you won't find
it in a thousand stationery stores...

472
00:35:02,160 --> 00:35:04,134
throughout the world.

473
00:35:04,207 --> 00:35:07,785
It's the same with the ink,
and the same with the wax.

474
00:35:07,855 --> 00:35:10,092
And your Las Vegas postmark?

475
00:35:10,160 --> 00:35:13,837
You can check it out, but I'll bet you
it came from a remailing service.

476
00:35:13,903 --> 00:35:16,139
Las Vegas would be
the last place he'd be.

477
00:35:16,208 --> 00:35:19,110
It'd be an assault
on his sense of taste.

478
00:35:25,456 --> 00:35:29,230
Don't you feel eyes
moving over your body, Clarice?

479
00:35:29,296 --> 00:35:30,921
I hardly see how you couldn't.

480
00:35:31,824 --> 00:35:34,922
And don't your eyes move
over the things you want?

481
00:35:36,207 --> 00:35:38,095
All right, then. Tell me how.

482
00:35:38,159 --> 00:35:39,436
No.

483
00:35:39,504 --> 00:35:41,576
It's your turn to tell me, Clarice.

484
00:35:41,647 --> 00:35:45,837
You don't have any more vacations
to sell on Anthrax Island.

485
00:35:45,903 --> 00:35:47,943
Quid pro quo, Clarice.

486
00:35:48,015 --> 00:35:50,732
I tell you things,
you tell me things.

487
00:35:50,799 --> 00:35:54,061
Not about this case.
About yourself.

488
00:35:54,127 --> 00:35:55,687
Quid pro quo.

489
00:35:55,759 --> 00:35:58,542
Yes or no, Clarice?

